Steven Taschuk wrote:

&gt; Quoth Anantha Lakshmi:
&gt; &gt; [...] I&#39;ve created a TestSuite, which contains
&gt; &gt; sequence of Tests. I want to find out the &quot;Time Taken
&gt; &gt; for each Test case in a Test suite&quot; while running the
&gt; &gt; Test Suite. [...]
&gt;
&gt; Ant&#39;s &lt;junit&gt; task does this, with &lt;formatter type=&#39;plain&#39;/&gt;.
&gt;
&gt; If you don&#39;t want to use Ant, it seems to me you can write the
&gt; functionality yourself with not so much work.  Something like this:
&gt;
&gt;   1. If you&#39;re writing your own implementations of Test
&gt;      (instead of, say, using TestCases), then make sure
&gt;      they call TestResult.startTest() and .endTest()
&gt;      in their run() methods.
&gt;
&gt;   2. Subclass java.textui.TestRunner, overriding the
&gt;      protected method createTestResult(); something like
&gt;
&gt;            protected TestResult createTestResult() {
&gt;                    TestResult result = super.createTestResult();
&gt;                    result.addTestListener( new TimingTestListener() );
&gt;                    return result;
&gt;            }
&gt;
&gt;   3. Write the TimingTestListener; a trivial version:
&gt;
&gt;            public class TimingTestListener implements TestListener {
&gt;                    private long start;
&gt;                    public void startTest( Test test ) {
&gt;                            start = new Date().getTime();
&gt;                    }
&gt;                    public void endTest( Test test ) {
&gt;                            System.out.println( test.toString() + &quot;: &quot;
&gt;                                    + (new Date().getTime() - start)
&gt;                                    + &quot;ms&quot; );
&gt;                    }
&gt;                    // ... the rest of the TestListener interface ...
&gt;            }
&gt;
&gt; And that would be it.  I haven&#39;t tested this, it&#39;s just off the
&gt; top of my head, and I don&#39;t actually know what I&#39;m talking about,
&gt; so I invite comments and corrections.
&gt;
&gt; (One obvious point: what TimingTestListener should actually do is
&gt; accumulate the results and provide methods for retrieving the
&gt; information later.  Also you might want to think about the
&gt; possibility that your tests might someday be run concurrently in
&gt; multiple threads, with one TestResult -- and hence one
&gt; TimingTestListener -- shared among all those threads.  The
&gt; implementation suggested above would fail miserably in such a
&gt; scenario.)
